There are about 13,000 Pacific giant salamanders in British Columbia.

Other Name(s): Nihonishigameor, ornate wood turtle, Honduran wood turtle, black river turtle, spot-legged turtle, brown land turtle, Splengleri turtle
Habitat: Deciduous forests, rain forests, marshes, bogs, rivers, streams
Location: North America, Central America, South America, China, Vietnam, Japan

name: Woodlouse
Fun Fact: This animal can roll up into a ball

name: Woodlouse Spider
Fun Fact: Unlike most spiders, woodlouse spiders don’t build a web.
Habitat: Woodpiles, inside brick walls, basements, damp cellars
Location: North America, South America, Australia, Asia, Europe, Africa

name: Woodpecker
Fun Fact: They have zygodactyl feet, with the first and fourth toes facing backward, the second and third facing forward, so they can grip tree trunks more efficiently
Slogan: There are 200 different species!
Nesting Location: Holes in the trunks of trees
Age of Molting: late summer within the first year

name: Woodrat
Fun Fact: Pack rats love shiny objects and will steal your jewelry.
Habitat: Deserts, mountains, caves, cliffs, woodlands, human habitations
Predators: Birds of prey, humans, foxes, weasels, bobcats, coyotes, skunks, snakes

name: Woolly Mammoth
Fun Fact: Some people want to bring the woolly mammoth back using preserved genetic evidence!
Biggest Threat: Wolves, cave hyenas, large predatory cats, environment change, and climate change
Slogan: Tusks grew to 16ft long!
Distinctive Feature: Enormous tusks

name: Woolly Monkey
Slogan: Has a long, strong prehensile tail!

name: Woolly Rhinoceros
Fun Fact: The woolly rhinoceros roamed the earth between three and a half million and 14,000 years ago.
Most Distinctive Feature: Thick, reddish brown fur, two large keratin horns

name: Worm
Fun Fact: Doesn’t have eyes.
Predators: Small mammals, birds, amphibians, reptiles, other insects

name: Worm Snake
Prey: Caterpillars, snails, slugs, and other soft-bodied invertebrates
Fun Fact: They emit a bad-smelling liquid if they are picked up!
Most Distinctive Feature: They have spiked tails but they don't sting!
Other Name(s): Blind snakes, thunder snakes, milk snakes, eastern twig snakes, and cricket snakes
Distinctive Feature: Narrow, cone-shaped heads
Nesting Location: Abandoned burrows, in decaying wood, or under rocks

name: Wrasse
Slogan: There are more than 500 different species!
Distinctive Feature: Large, thick lips and protractile mouths

name: Writing Spider
Prey: dragonflies, flies, mosquitos, tree bugs, beetles
Fun Fact: males pluck webs like strings on a guitar
Habitat: near bodies of water and shrubbery
Predators: humans, jumping spiders, spider wasps, and birds

name: Wrought Iron Butterflyfish
Fun Fact: Is endemic to Japan.

name: Wyoming Toad
Slogan: Releases poison from neck glands for defense!

name: X-Ray Tetra
Fun Fact: Yellow, black and white striped fins!
Slogan: Yellow, black and white striped fins!
Distinctive Feature: Striped fins and translucent skin

name: Xerus
Fun Fact: Xerus use their fluffy tail as shade from the sun on the African savanna.
Slogan: Squirrel that lives in burrows in Africa.

name: Xoloitzcuintli
Fun Fact: The Xoloitzcuintli is the national dog of Mexico

name: Yak
Slogan: There are only a few left in the wild!

name: Yakutian Laika
Fun Fact: The Yakute people were likely the first to use dogs to pull sleds, so the Yakutian Laika was probably among the first sled dogs.

name: Yarara
Prey: Youngers snakes eat insects, toads, frogs and smaller reptiles. Adults prefer rodents and other small mammals.
Fun Fact: Females are much larger than males
Most Distinctive Feature: Vivid brown to black trapezoidal marks edged in white or cream
Habitat: South American forests, marshes, swamps, grasslands, and riverine habitats
Common Name: Yarara, crossed pit viper, urutu, wutu
Predators: Birds of prey, including the burrowing owls
Distinctive Feature: The snake's belly is pale with a single dark stripe that runs the entire length of its body

name: Yellow Cobra
Fun Fact: The Yellow Cobra belong to one of the most dangerous families in the world.

name: Yellow Sac Spider
Fun Fact: Primarily Carnivorous, but sometimes snacks on nectar.
Litter Size: 5 egg sacs per nest, 40 eggs each

name: Yellow Spotted Lizard
Fun Fact: Gives birth to live young.
Other Name(s): Yellow-spotted tropical night lizard, yellow-spotted night lizard.
Habitat: Rainforests, tropical dry forests, subtropical wet forests, and in water.

name: Yellow-Bellied Sea Snake
Prey: Fish, including mullets, jacks, anchovies, and damselfish
Fun Fact: Sea snakes spend approximately 90% of their lives under water.
Distinctive Feature: Paddle-shaped tail

name: Yellow-Eyed Penguin
Slogan: The rarest species of penguin!
Distinctive Feature: Bright yellow head-band and pink coloured feet

name: Yellowfin Tuna
Fun Fact: The yellowfin forms schools with other tuna species
Predators: Sharks, whales, marlins, seabirds, humans, and other fish

name: Yeti Crab
Fun Fact: The yeti crab has hairy arms, which collect bacteria to feed on
Most Distinctive Feature: The white body and hairy claws

name: Yoranian
Fun Fact: These dogs are very intelligent and are great with children.
Biggest Threat: Being crushed by larger animals or humans
Temperament: Friendly, alert, over-protective, intelligent, easy to train, and great with children
Training: easy to train

name: Yorkie Bichon
Fun Fact: Yorkie Bichons can come in a wide range of colors including black, white, blonde, gray, golden, or dark brown.

name: Yorkie-poo
Fun Fact: The Yorkie-Poo originated from the hybrid poodle phase of the late 20th century

name: Yorkshire Terrier
Fun Fact: Yorkies hold many records for smallest dog.
Slogan: Highly energetic and eager for adventure!

name: Zebra
Fun Fact: Stripe patterns are unique to each individual!
Most Distinctive Feature: Long, slender legs and one toe on each foot
Other Name(s): Mountain Zebra, Common Zebra, Plains Zebra, Burchells Zebra, Grevys Zebra
Slogan: Stripe patterns are unique to each individual!

name: Zebra Finch
Fun Fact: The male zebra finch creates a unique song by drawing inspiration from its parent or tutor
Most Distinctive Feature: The speckled or striped plumage along the sides and tail
Predators: Marsupials, snakes, mice, and birds of prey

name: Zebra Mussels
Prey: Plankton, waste and debris from water
Fun Fact: A female zebra mussel can deposit 30,000 to 1,000,000 eggs each year!
Most Distinctive Feature: Alternating dark and light stripes on outer shells

name: Zebra Pleco
Prey: Algae, detritus, and small organic matter
Fun Fact: The zebra pleco is a bottom feeder with a sucker mouth.

name: Zebra Shark
Slogan: Can get to be 30 years old in the wild!

name: Zebra Snake
Prey: rodents, birds, fish, eggs, other reptiles
Fun Fact: The zebra snake is a black-hooded species of spitting cobra native to several of the southern countries of Africa.
Common Name: western barred spitting cobra, zebra cobra, zebra snake

name: Zebra Spitting Cobra
Fun Fact: This snake can spit a distance of nine feet or further!

name: Zebu
Slogan: There are around 75 different species!

name: Zonkey
Fun Fact: The offspring of Zebra and Donkey parents!
Most Distinctive Feature: Unique stripes darkest on belly and legs
Slogan: The offspring of Zebra and Donkey parents!

name: Zorse
Fun Fact: The offspring of a Zebra and Horse parents!
Most Distinctive Feature: Unique dark stripes are boldest on legs
Slogan: The offspring of a Zebra and Horse parents!

name: Zuchon
Fun Fact: The breed often changes colors throughout its life, with its puppy coat becoming lighter over the first few years of life, then darkening as he ages.
